[done] make fixtures to test _FLAGS and _AX register usage against the real BCC.
  → fixtures 4051-4062 (pseudo-registers + _FLAGS bit-mask recognizer);
    see memory: bcc-pseudo-register-codegen.

  `if (_FLAGS & 0x1)` -> direct `jnc`. The whole jumpable-flag table maps:
    CF/PF/ZF/SF/OF -> `jnc`/`jnp`/`jne`/`jns`/`jno` (skip-then).
    `!(_FLAGS & bit)` inverts to the set-jump. Value context falls back
    to `pushf; pop ax; and ax, K`.
  `_AX = 0xabcd` -> bare `mov ax, imm16`. `return _AX` is free.
  `if (_AL == 0x80)` -> direct `cmp al, imm8`, no widening.
  `_AL` widens unsigned (zero-extend via `mov ah, 0`).

[done] Take a look at segment prefixes used in type declarations
  → fixtures 4063-4068; see memory: bcc-segment-qualified-pointers.

  `int _ss/_es/_cs/_ds *p` is always 2 bytes regardless of memory model.
  Qualifier becomes a TASM `<seg>:` override on the deref operand. DS
  elided (default segment). Large model (-ml) preserves near-ness: the
  function turns far but the seg-qualified pointer stays a single word.

[done] Segment pointers (_seg)
  → fixtures 4069-4074; see memory: bcc-seg-pointers.

  `char _seg *p` is a 2-byte segment selector. Deref pattern:
    mov es, word ptr [<seg-ptr>]      ; load segment into ES
    mov <reg>, byte ptr es:[<off>]    ; offset becomes displacement
  Offset can be 0, a constant, or a near pointer (-> SI). The seg+near
  -> far semantic is realized purely by the addressing mode.
  `(unsigned)p` is identity at codegen.

  Distinct from the `_es` qualifier: `_es *` assumes ES is already set
  (just emits the override); `_seg *` actively loads ES at every deref.

  Full PSP example from the original TODO not yet fixtured end-to-end
  (combines _seg + near ptr + putchar loop). Pieces are covered by
  4069-4074 individually.
